observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the LCE direct:
the GSO, together with the inventory committee, to conduct the physical count of inventories accurately and completely in accordance with the above-mentioned provisions to fairly present the Inventory account in the financial statements;
the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to conduct a periodic reconciliation of the Inventory account to ensure that the balance of the said account on their separate records is reconciled at year end.

We recommended that the:
Revenue Collectors strictly comply with the daily remittance of collections and in full amount to the Liquidating Officer, and likewise, the Liquidating Officer and the Municipal Treasurer to deposit all their collections intact daily, or not later than the next banking day;
Municipal Treasurer, stop the issuance of accountable forms to accountable officers who have pending unremitted collections;
Revenue Collectors and the Municipal Treasurer properly record collections and remittances on the cashbooks in the manner they transpired; and consistently provide the actual dates of deposit of collections on the cashbook.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

a.	directs the accountant to make necessary adjustments on the proper recognition of the BGCM and also, require the submission of the lacking documents on various expenses;

b.	ensure that utilization of the BGCM for COVID related PPAs are within the prescribed duration stated in Section 3.8 of LBC No. 125;

c.	require the BAC to submit an explanation or justification for purchase of commercial rice instead of NFA rice amounting to ₱3,455,000.00.  

d.	directs the Municipal Treasurer and Accountant to prepare and submit the monthly Report on Fund Utilization and Status of Program/Project/Activity Implementation.

We recommended that the LCE instructs the LDRRMO to:

a. include all the unexpended prior year balances in its LDRRMFIP and use the format specified in Annex A of COA Circular No. 2012-002;

b. detailed PPAs and its corresponding appropriations be classified as either MOOE or Capital Outlay in the LDRRMFIP;

c. submit the monthly report on sources and utilization on or before the 15th day after the end of each month through the LDRRMC and Local Development Council (LDC) to the COA auditor of the LGU; and

d. maximize the implementation of the PPAs under the 70% Mitigation Fund to increase the Municipality’s level of preparedness during natural calamities.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

a.)	Direct the Inventory Committee, if any, to complete the conduct of physical inventory of all properties of LGU;

b.)	Direct the GSO to submit the complete Report of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) to the Audit Team; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant & the GSO to maintain appropriate Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards (PPELC) and Property Cards (PC), respectively and Conduct a period reconciliation of records in accordance with Sec\tion 124 of NGAS Manual for LGU Volume I.

Direct the property unit to prove the existence of the ICT Equipment in the amount of P919,940.55 and present the Acknowledgement Receipt of Equipment (ARE) to determine the accountability thereof;
Direct the accountant and property unit to reconcile the deficiencies noted in the amount of P9,903,515.98;

Direct the GSO or Municipal Treasurer to provide a complete list of all donated PPEs;

We recommended that the management:

a.)	Fast track the implementation of the Programs/Projects/Activities (PPAs) consistent with the Memorandum of Agreements (MOAs) for the intended beneficiaries;

b.)	Return to the Source Agency the unutilized fund for projects already completed in accordance to COA Circular 94-013.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

a.)	fast track the on implementation of the PPAs consistent with the Memorandum of Agreements for the benefit of intended beneficiaries;

b.)	revisit the MOA with the source agency for provision on the return of excess fund. Immediately prepare the check, when clearly stated. Otherwise, revert the amount to the General Fund.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. Directs the Inventory Committee, if any, to complete the conduct inventory of all properties of LGU;
b. Direct the GSO to submit the complete Report of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) to the Auditor concerned not later than January 31 of the following year;
c. Direct the Municipal Accountant & the GSO to maintain appropriate Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards (PLC) and Property Cards (PC), respectively and Conduct a period reconciliation of records in accordance with Section 124 of NGAS Manual for LGU;
d. direct the property unit to prove the existence of the ICT Equipment in the amount of P919,940.55 and present the Acknowledgement Receipt of Equipment (ARE) to determine the accountability thereof;
e. direct the accountant and property unit to reconcile the deficiencies noted in the amount of P9,903,515.98;
f. direct the GSO or Municipal Treasurer to provide a complete list of all donated PPEs;

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor or his representative to:
 direct the property unit to prove the existence of the ICT Equipment in the amount of
P919,940.55 and present the Property
Acknowledgement Receipt (PAR) to determine the
accountability thereof;
 create an Inventory Committee which will conduct the physical count of inventory every
year-end;
 direct the accountant and property unit to reconcile the deficiencies noted in the amount of
P9,903,515.98;
 direct the property unit to conduct annual physical count of PPE, prepare and submit
complete inventory reports to the auditor promptly and maintain Property Cards (PCs) on
each item of PPE; instruct the accounting unit to maintain Property, Plant and
Equipment Ledger Cards (PPELCs) and facilitate reconciliation of records;
 direct the GSO or Municipal Treasurer to provide a complete list of all donated PPEs;
 direct the Accountant to make the necessary adjusting entries for unrecorded depreciation.

We recommend that the:
 OIC-Municipal Treasurer submit immediately to the Municipal
Accountant all liquidation for the outstanding cash advances;
 Municipal Accountant support the credits made to the accounts with
complete documentation and supporting schedules, and submit the
same to the audit team;
 Local Chief Executive, OIC-Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal
Accountant submit justifications on deficiency;
 Concerned agency officials and employees adhere strictly to the rules
and regulations on cash advances.
